    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-11-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-11-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="545"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d545">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">841.857 M 331/42</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to President
                            <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-11-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 22, 1916</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I enclose the report of our
                    Consul at Cork, Mr. Frost, dated November 1st,<note n="65" xml:id="d545fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> in the case of the <hi rend="italic">Marina</hi>, to which
                    is attached the affidavits of the American citizens who were <pb facs="0642"
                        n="574" xml:id="pg_574"/> on board the vessel. I also enclose the report of
                    the Consul dated November 2d on the same subject.<note n="66" xml:id="d545fn2"
                        >Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>It seems to me to be a case in which, from the facts sworn to, there appears to
                    be little possible defense. Even the excuse that the vessel was laden with
                    contraband for Great Britain is absent, in the fact that she was on her homeward
                    voyage and practically in ballast.</p>
                <p>I have been considering in my own mind whether it is possible for us to avoid
                    taking definite action in the case in accordance with our <hi rend="italic"
                        >Sussex</hi> note. I do not feel, however, that I wish to express an opinion
                    at present, although I consider the situation very grave.</p>
                <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
